<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1889-11-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1889-11-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="350" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">King</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1889-11-08"><hi rend="italic">November</hi> 8,
                            1889</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 29.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 33 of the 12th
                        ultimo, referring to a note verbale received in February last, from the
                        Sublime Porte, regarding the military service of cavasses and dragomans
                        employed by foreign consulates.</p>
                    <p>The terms of your proposed reply to the note of February are approved. It is
                        hoped that the exemption sought for our employés, not being claimed as a
                        right, will be conceded as a favor, so that the business of our officers in
                        Turkey may not be embarrassed by the abrupt withdrawal of such experienced
                        persons from our service.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
            </body></text></TEI>